 Debounce function: This function delays the execution of a function for a specified amount of time after it has been called, preventing multiple executions of the same function in quick succession.

```javascript
function debounce(func, wait, immediate) {
  var timeout;
  return function() {
    var context = this,
      args = arguments;
    var later = function() {
      timeout = null;
      if (!immediate) func.apply(context, args);
    };
    var callNow = immediate && !timeout;
    clearTimeout(timeout);
    timeout = setTimeout(later, wait);
    if (callNow) func.apply(context, args);
  };
}
```

Example usage:

```javascript
// Define a function that updates the UI with new data
function updateUI(data) {
  // Update the UI with the new data
};

// Debounce the updateUI function to prevent multiple updates in quick succession
var debouncedUpdateUI = debounce(updateUI, 500);

// Call the debounced function with new data
setTimeout(debouncedUpdateUI, 1000, [1, 2, 3, 4, 5]);
```

In this example, the `updateUI` function is debounced using the `debounce` function. The debounced function, `debouncedUpdateUI`, is then called with new data after a delay of 500 milliseconds. When `debouncedUpdateUI` is called, it checks if it has already been called recently and if not, it calls the original `updateUI` function with the new data. This prevents multiple updates of the UI with the same data in quick succession.
